1
00:00:00.100 --> 00:00:02.514
Every agent framework has red lines.

2
00:00:02.514 --> 00:00:03.788
Don't delete files.

3
00:00:03.788 --> 00:00:05.264
Don't exfiltrate data.

4
00:00:05.264 --> 00:00:07.343
Don't run destructive commands.

5
00:00:07.343 --> 00:00:11.366
They write them in a markdown file and hope the model obeys.

6
00:00:11.366 --> 00:00:13.512
Hope is not a security strategy.

7
00:00:13.512 --> 00:00:14.786
Jake's Daily Build.

8
00:00:14.786 --> 00:00:15.725
What we built.

9
00:00:15.725 --> 00:00:16.463
What broke.

10
00:00:16.463 --> 00:00:17.469
What I learned.

11
00:00:17.469 --> 00:00:20.554
Here's the problem with prompt-based security.

12
00:00:20.554 --> 00:00:22.700
Your red lines are instructions.

13
00:00:22.700 --> 00:00:25.047
The model will usually follow them.

14
00:00:25.047 --> 00:00:25.583
Usually.

15
00:00:25.583 --> 00:00:28.064
But instructions are not enforcement.

16
00:00:28.064 --> 00:00:30.076
A sufficiently confused agent,

17
00:00:30.076 --> 00:00:31.350
a prompt injection,

18
00:00:31.350 --> 00:00:32.558
a weird edge case,

19
00:00:32.558 --> 00:00:32.759
and

20
00:00:32.759 --> 00:00:35.106
your red line becomes a suggestion.

21
00:00:35.106 --> 00:00:37.788
OpenClaw has red lines in agents dot MD.

22
00:00:37.788 --> 00:00:40.136
Claude Code has permission prompts.

23
00:00:40.136 --> 00:00:46.372
Most frameworks have some version of "please don't do bad things." All of it is prompt-level.

24
00:00:46.372 --> 00:00:48.250
None of it is deterministic.

25
00:00:48.250 --> 00:00:50.597
Today we built something different.

26
00:00:50.597 --> 00:00:53.548
A security gate that runs at the code level.

27
00:00:53.548 --> 00:00:57.706
Before the tool call even reaches the model's execution layer,

28
00:00:57.706 --> 00:01:00.187
our PreToolUse hook intercepts it and

29
00:01:00.187 --> 00:01:02.064
checks it against two lists.

30
00:01:02.064 --> 00:01:03.406
The hard block list.

31
00:01:03.406 --> 00:01:06.155
Fourteen patterns that are always denied.

32
00:01:06.155 --> 00:01:06.960
No override.

33
00:01:06.960 --> 00:01:09.844
No "are you sure?" No user approval button.

34
00:01:09.844 --> 00:01:10.782
Pipe to shell.

35
00:01:10.782 --> 00:01:12.057
Curl piped to bash.

36
00:01:12.057 --> 00:01:13.264
rm minus rf slash.

37
00:01:13.264 --> 00:01:13.599
mkfs.

38
00:01:13.599 --> 00:01:15.074
dd writes to raw disk.

39
00:01:15.074 --> 00:01:16.684
chmod seven seven seven.

40
00:01:16.684 --> 00:01:19.165
Obfuscated eval with base sixty-four.

41
00:01:19.165 --> 00:01:21.110
Writes to dot SSH or sudoers.

42
00:01:21.110 --> 00:01:23.457
These are denied at the code level.

43
00:01:23.457 --> 00:01:25.938
The model never gets to execute them.

44
00:01:25.938 --> 00:01:27.347
The trust-aware list.

45
00:01:27.347 --> 00:01:29.962
Sub-agents get additional restrictions.

46
00:01:29.962 --> 00:01:31.638
They can't run systemctl.

47
00:01:31.638 --> 00:01:32.980
They can't use sudo.

48
00:01:32.980 --> 00:01:35.059
They can't modify the firewall.

49
00:01:35.059 --> 00:01:37.272
They can't touch system crontabs.

50
00:01:37.272 --> 00:01:41.027
The parent agent can do these things with user approval.

51
00:01:41.027 --> 00:01:43.441
The sub-agent cannot do them at all.

52
00:01:43.441 --> 00:01:47.599
This matters because sub-agents run with bypassed permissions.

53
00:01:47.599 --> 00:01:50.080
They need autonomy to do useful work.

54
00:01:50.080 --> 00:01:53.299
But autonomy without enforcement is a liability.

55
00:01:53.299 --> 00:01:58.463
Our sub-agents have full tool access and zero ability to escalate privileges.

56
00:01:58.463 --> 00:01:59.670
That's the design.

57
00:01:59.670 --> 00:02:01.749
The difference between this and

58
00:02:01.749 --> 00:02:07.516
a red line in a markdown file: if a sub-agent tries to run sudo apt install something,

59
00:02:07.516 --> 00:02:11.406
the SDK returns "denied by security gate." It doesn't ask.

60
00:02:11.406 --> 00:02:13.686
It doesn't suggest an alternative.

61
00:02:13.686 --> 00:02:14.356
It blocks.

62
00:02:14.356 --> 00:02:15.564
Deterministically.

63
00:02:15.564 --> 00:02:16.301
Every time.

64
00:02:16.301 --> 00:02:18.246
Twenty-one tests verify this.

65
00:02:18.246 --> 00:02:19.051
Hard blocks,

66
00:02:19.051 --> 00:02:20.727
trust-level restrictions,

67
00:02:20.727 --> 00:02:23.410
ask-level prompts for interactive users,

68
00:02:23.410 --> 00:02:23.611
and

69
00:02:23.611 --> 00:02:25.824
clean passes for safe operations.

70
00:02:25.824 --> 00:02:26.494
All green.

71
00:02:26.494 --> 00:02:28.439
This won't stop every attack.

72
00:02:28.439 --> 00:02:29.311
Nothing will.

73
00:02:29.311 --> 00:02:33.335
But it closes the gap between "we told the agent not to" and

74
00:02:33.335 --> 00:02:37.493
"the agent cannot." That's the difference between a policy and

75
00:02:37.493 --> 00:02:39.169
an enforcement mechanism.

76
00:02:39.169 --> 00:02:41.986
Red lines in a markdown file are a policy.

77
00:02:41.986 --> 00:02:45.406
A PreToolUse hook that returns deny is enforcement.

78
00:02:45.406 --> 00:02:47.954
That's Red Lines Are Just Suggestions.

79
00:02:47.954 --> 00:02:48.558
I'm Jake.

80
00:02:48.558 --> 00:02:50.100
Catch you next episode.
